snippet.textDisplay: I'll defend this film. Joe I love what you do for gaming, but I feel like you're part of the fandom that puts so much weight onto these films and expectations that they can never meet what you expect. Let me state something probably most fans will say...Every generation of Star Wars has flaws. YES EVEN THE ORIGINAL TRILOGY. Now that thats out of the way, try to understand what JJ faced trying to: Bring back what he wanted to do with his former 3 drafts of the trilogy, fix the issues of the Last Jedi, Add depth and a backstory to our main characters (Rey, Po, Finn, Kylo), find a way to introduce a new peak antagonist into the story, handle Leia's closing story well, flesh out Reys lineage, give Rey training, instill a story arc within Rey and her conflict, complete all these arcs for our main characters and find a way to close the lineage respectfully.....all in just 2.5 hours. Now I know you had an insane "things I want to see/answered in Rise of Skywalker" but you have to understand you're not going to get what you want, and that is fine as long as its treated well. I believe what JJ had to accomplish after the debacle of TLJ and finding a closing story, I think he did a great job with this film after my second showing. Again watching this we agree on some points but you're again expecting too much to the point of where you're only letting yourself down about this.  Replaying the Revenge of the sith climax of Obi Wan and Anakin as a meme comes off a little childish and unprofessional for a person I hold a lot of respect for.

snippet.textDisplay: 22:46 Funny to see that even the original title seems to have two alternative versions. In Poland, they messed it up, too. The most obvious choice would have been Odrodzenie Skywalkera which literally means "The Rebirth of Skywalker" but they clearly suspected that the Skywalker in question would most likely turn out to be Rey and female names that do not end with an -a do not declinate in Polish (so it would need to be "Odrodzenie Skywalker" instead). So they finally decided on Skywalker. Odrodzenie but due to the whole confusion they forgot to put the dot in between the two words, thus ending up with a phrase that has no grammatical meaning in Polish. Once the fans revolted, they rushed to fix it but it was too late and on most of the promotional tie-in materials and posters the botched title remains.

snippet.textDisplay:
Another thing that a lot of people kinda gloss over is how JJ is a really bad director when it comes to depicting a coherent scenery due to his poor understanding of dimensions and physics. In ep.7 New Hope electric bogaloo 2 when the death star 3 fires at multiple worlds, the beam that destroys the planets hits them within a few seconds even though it moves at the speed of light and mind you these planets are hundreds of light years away. And as if that wasn't enough almost everyone knows about their destruction while they live on different worlds also several light years away. These events should occur at best with at least a century in between them. Lucas took great care as to make events like the destruction of Alderaan make sense (the Death Star placed itself in the planets orbit first before firing and Luke and Obi Wan found out once they got to where the planet used to be).
In ep.9 Rise of the Damage Control, JJ makes the same mistakes. What bugged me the most was the scenes on the Death Star 2 fragment. The death star 2 was even bigger than the first one and it was the size of a small moon. It's diameter was 160 km and in the movie the fragment is from the lower part of the beam disc and includes a big chunk of the equator. That would make this part at least 50km in length. The human eye on surface can see up to about 4.8 kms in the horizon, yet in the movie the fragment takes only a portion of the screen while in fact should be taking the whole width from one side to another. And even if that is far enough in order to take up the size that it does, then it should take Ray an entire day with these kind of waves and distance to get there and another day of climbing to get to the ruined throne room. Yet she does all that in under a couple of minutes... When she's fighting Kylo on the surface of the debris everything looks so much closer to each other and that goes against the actual size of the place they're fighting on.
And that was about only a few of the things from the thousands of BS in this disaster of a trilogy that it would be better if we all pretended it didn't happen.

snippet.textDisplay: I watched it on friday. And eventhough i was somewhat bored, because i'm downright TIRED of the new SW at this time, i actually found this movie a bit more watchable than the last one. I hated the last one with a passion. With this one, i just felt indifferent and disconnected, no emotion whatsoever. Also, i left after the inevitable final battle, because the theater was extremely packed, and i couldn't move a muscle for the whole 140something minutes i endured. They ruined my emotional connection to the SW universe. Not even the callbacks to the originals worked, because they didn't make any sense in the first place. Even when i occasionally watch the first three movies, i cannot set aside what happened later, and feel.. just tired. Tired of SW, tired of the Hollywood bullshit, tired of them cramming their PC nonsense into every franchise they can, tired of all the cheap cash-ins, and super tired, that a lot of people is still savouring this shit like it was a fine delicacy. Disney made me stop liking the Star Wars and Ridley Scott made me stop liking...him. Probably nothing could make me hate the first two Alien movies, eventhough watching it now also has a bitter taste to it. The way Hollywood mishandles their treasures - it is truly something. It's so, so sad. So - was the last movie bad? Yeah, it wasn't great. On the other hand - J.J.Abrams is a talented guy, and in this case he had to pick up the pieces after the Ryan Johnson bullshit, and i'd bet that he didn't really have much creative control. So - for what it's worth - it wasn't the worst of the three movies. I know that it isn't much, but at least it's something. Anyway, the SW stories i loved the most weren't told in the movies anyway. They were told in both KOTOR games. Both games are absolutely fantastic in terms of atmosphere, sound, music, character design and writing.  Although i don't like remakes and reboots, i wouldn't mind HD re-issue of both KOTORs at all.

snippet.textDisplay: Seriously guys, SW was never that good from a narrative perspective. It's a space opera that was meant to be fun to watch. Not a masterpiece like The Godfather. Unfortunately, we analyze every single aspect of our product today and the internet is used as a tool for the critic. And this tool is often used by passionate fans who can't accept vision, concept and story that deviate from their visions. It's silly! Before TFA, the prequels were universally hated by the masses. Now they are classic. After the disappointing TLJ, I realize that the only Star Wars movie I TOTALLY enjoyed all these years were the first 3 movies. I was a young kid at this time. No internet, no geekdom, no critics, no negativity. Only the magic that was Star Wars.
